{
  "result": "At dawn, the city briefly belongs to ordinary miracles. The bakery unlocks its door and lets out a cloud of warm bread; a bus sighs at the curb; pigeons hold a conference on the statue\u2019s shoulders. For a few minutes, everyone seems undecided about who they must become.\n\nI like that hour because it forgives unfinished things. The email not sent, the apology rehearsed but not spoken, the plant drooping on the windowsill: all of them wait in a softer light. Morning does not ask for triumph. It merely offers a clean surface and says, try.\n\nWe talk often about big changes, as if life were a staircase we climb by dramatic leaps. But most transformation is granular. It hides in choosing water before coffee, listening for one extra second, putting the keys in the same bowl, opening the window when the room feels stale. Tiny acts are seeds with excellent memories.\n\nBy evening the city grows theatrical. Neon signs bloom, conversations spill from restaurants, and every apartment window becomes a small square of weather: blue television light, amber lamps, the silver flicker of someone cooking alone. I pass by and imagine countless private beginnings.\n\nPerhaps that is enough: not a grand philosophy, but attention. To notice the bread, the bus, the drooping plant, the hand searching for another hand in a crowd. If we keep faith with these minor wonders, the larger world may feel less like a problem to solve and more like a place to inhabit together.",
